<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="lesson5_3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title> Quantum State Representation: Bra-Ket</title>

  <p>Let's start our exploration of quantum state representations with bra-ket notation.</p>

  <section
    xml:id="bra_ket_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket Quantum Representation</title>

    <p> The purpose of <term>bra-ket notation</term> is to express the probability of each potential
      outcome. Therefore, there are two parts: The probability and the outcome.</p>

    <p> Bra-ket notation favors ease of calculation over easy readability of the probability,
      but it is easier to read than its alternative, vector notation.</p>

    <p> Each outcome is expressed in a <term>ket</term>, which you've already seen in this textbook: <m>\ket{0}</m>
      , <m>\ket{+}</m>, etc. </p>

    <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
      <p> In the figure to the right, we are expressing the probabilities of measuring apples or
        bananas. Each term in the expression represents a single outcome and are <em>added
          together</em>. The outcome (apple or banana) is placed inside of the ket, and the <term>probability
        amplitude</term> (rather than the probability) is placed just before the ket. </p>

      <image source="L5.3.braket.png" width="66%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <p> The relationship between probability amplitude and probability is:</p>

    <p>
      <md>\text{probability} = |\text{probability amplitude}|^2</md>
    </p>

    <p> In this notation, if there is equal probability, or 1/2 probability of each of two
      outcomes,
      then it will be: </p>

    <p>
      <insert>picture like the one above with apples and bananas but with the terms 1/rt(2)
        for each</insert>
    </p>

    <p>
      <insert>Put in a question here using heads or tails coins in bra-ket notation and ask what the
        probability is of each outcome.</insert>
    </p>

    <exercise label="Bra-Ket Heads and Tails">
      <title>Coin Flip in Bra-Ket Notation</title>
      <idx>bra-ket coin flip</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>If <m>H</m> is heads and <m>T</m> is tails, what is the probability of getting heads and
          tails for the following state?</p>
        <p>
          <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{H} + \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}} \ket{T}</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! By squaring each probability amplitude, you get the probability of
              getting the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Remember that the bra-ket notation shows probability amplitudes, not probability.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{2}{3}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you associate the probability with the corresponding outcome.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of heads, <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> chance of tails</p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>This is a special coin! Make sure you check probabilities from the bra-ket notation.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Bra-ket notation uses probability amplitudes, which are squared to get probabilities.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>


    <p> We can see that this notation is very flexible to represent all kinds of probabilities. If
      we want to express outcomes from the raincoat/raining example from (<xref
        ref="sec-independent-probabilities" />), it would look like the following:</p>

    <p>50% chance of sun, 50% chance of rain:</p>
    <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{☀️} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
      \ket{🌧️}</md>

    <p>75% chance of no raincoat (👕), 25% chance of raincoat (🧥):</p>
    <md>\sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} \ket{👕} + \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}} \ket{🧥}
      = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \ket{👕} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{🧥}</md>

    <p>Remember: to compute probability amplitudes for bra-ket notation, calculate the <em>square
      root</em> of the probability of each outcome.</p>

    <p> In quantum computing, the possible values for a quantum bit (qubit) are 0 or 1. So
      a qubit in a 50/50 superposition of 0 and 1 would have the state: </p>

    <md>\ket{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </md>

    <p> If there is negative phase, then it will be placed on the 1 state: </p>
    <md>\ket{-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} </md>

    <p>
      <insert>A few exercises - give a state and answer the probabilities,
        give the probabilities and answer the state. Through in phase into one of them.</insert>
    </p>

  </section>

  <section
    xml:id="multi-qubit-bra_ket" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multi-Qubit Bra-Ket Notation</title>

    <p> We can also combine two independent qubits into a 2-qubit bra-ket notation, just like we
      represented two qubits using our visual representation (<xref ref="sec-two-qubit-visual" />).
      An individual qubit only has two possible outcomes: 0 or 1. For a pair of qubits, we have each
      combination of possible outcomes: 00, 01, 10, 11. The tricky part is how to calculate the
      probability of those combined events from the single qubit probabilities. This is when our
      independent probability calculations come into play <mdash /> you just multiply the
      appropriate values together. </p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.3.1to2qubitsbraket.png" width="60%" />
    </p>

    <p>This might look familiar: combining independent qubits is analogous to distribution when
      multiplying two additive terms in algebra!</p>

    <md>
      <mrow>(a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}) (c\ket{0} + d\ket{1}) \amp= ac\ket{00} + ad\ket{01} + bc\ket{10} +
        bd\ket{11}</mrow>
      <mrow>(ax + by) (cx + dy) \amp= ac(x^2) + ad(xy) + bc(yx) + bd(y^2)</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>You can also factor out combined qubit states, using the same algebra rules!
    </p>
    <md>\ket{00} + \ket{01} = \ket{0} (\ket{0} + \ket{1})</md>
    <p>However, the order of the individual qubits is highly important, because the order
      corresponds to each individual qubit in our system. Thus, multiplied terms <em>cannot</em> be
      reordered as in algebraic expressions.</p>
    <md>\ket{0} (\ket{0} + \ket{1}) \ne (\ket{0} + \ket{1}) \ket{0}</md>
    <p>It's important to note that not all multi-qubit states can be factored out into individual
      qubits, e.g. <m>\ket{00} + \ket{11}</m>. These states have fascinating implications in quantum computing, but
      we'll dig deeper into these states at a later time.</p>

    <p>
      <insert> Put in some questions here with 2 qubits and 3 qubits - can grab from my homeworks.</insert>
    </p>

  </section>

  <section
    xml:id="bra_ket_state_simplification" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Bra-Ket State Simplification</title>

    <p>Just like with fractions, there are multiple ways of expressing the same state. Every time a
      state is calculated, we then simplify the state into its preferred form. We saw some similar
      simplification rules for our visual representation in <xref
        ref="sec-simplify-superposition-visual" />. Let's learn a few simplification rules for
      bra-ket notation!</p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>The order of the outcomes is always in increasing numeric order
          (starting with all 0's and ending with all 1's). Below is a properly formed
          3-qubit state: </p>
        <md>a\ket{000} + b\ket{001} + c\ket{010} + d\ket{011} + e\ket{100} + f\ket{101} + g\ket{110}
          + h\ket{111}</md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>You may omit any term whose probability is 0. </p>
        <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + 0\ket{01} + 0\ket{10} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11} =
          \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</md>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>The first term in the state (the <term>leading term</term>) is never in negative phase.
          As we discussed previously (<xref ref="sec-global-phase" />), global phase has no physical
          meaning; so if the leading term is negative, you can multiply the whole state by <m>-1</m>
          and get an equivalent state.</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{01} -
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10} +
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</mrow>
          <mrow>= \amp\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{01} +
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10} -
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}</mrow>
        </md>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p> One rule that is different from algebraic expressions is that you can multiply all terms by
      the same number and the resulting state is the same; the <em>comparison</em> of the states is
      what matters, not the absolute values. However, the purpose of bra-ket notation is to be
      easily able to tell by looking at it what the probabilities of each outcome are (and still be
      able to perform operations). Therefore, we prefer to keep bra-ket states <term>
        normalized</term> .</p>

    <p> To normalize a bra-ket state, we want to ensure that the coefficients of each term represent
      probability amplitudes. In order to do so, the sum of the squares of each coefficient should
      add up to 1. This represents the fact that there is a 100% chance of getting any of the
      outcomes expressed in the state. For example, for a single qubit of the form <m>a\ket{0} + b\ket{1}</m>, <m>a^2 + b^2 = 1</m>.</p>

    <p>If all outcomes are the same probability some people omit the leading term.
      However, none of the answers in this book use this rule because it hides the true
      probability.</p>

    <p>
      <insert>exercises</insert>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="bra_ket_gate_operation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Calculating Quantum Gate Results</title>
    <p>Now that we have a way to represent quantum states, the natural next question is: how do we
      perform operations on these states? Bra-ket notation is handy to perform simple operations.
      Let's walk through an example.</p>

    <p>The general rule for applying a gate to a quantum state is to apply its effects to the
      appropriate qubit in each term of the bra-ket state. Let's first write down the effects of the
      gates we have looked at in bra-ket notation:</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>NOT</c> Gate </title>
      <p>
        <m>\ket{0} \xrightarrow{\text{NOT}} \ket{1}, \ket{1} \xrightarrow{\text{NOT}} \ket{0}</m>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>H</c> Gate </title>
      <p>
        <m>\ket{0} \xrightarrow{\text{H}} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1},
        \ket{1} \xrightarrow{\text{H}} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</m>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Now, when applying gates on a bra-ket state, all you need to do is apply this transformation
      on each term in the expression. Let's start with an example that you already know the result
      for: applying an <c>H</c> gate on the <m>\ket{+}</m> state. From our earlier discussions, we know that
      the output of this operation is <m>\ket{0}</m>. Let's use our brand-new mathematical model to verify
      this behavior! </p>

    <md>
      <mrow>\ket{+} \amp= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}</mrow>
      <mrow>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1} \amp\xrightarrow{\text{H}}
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \Big(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}\Big) +
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \Big(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \ket{1}\Big) </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \frac{1}{2} \ket{0} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{1} + \frac{1}{2} \ket{0} - \frac{1}{2}
        \ket{1} </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \ket{0}</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>What about two-qubit gates, like <c>SWAP</c> or <c>CNOT</c>?</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>SWAP</c> Gate</title>
      <p> For <c>SWAP</c> gates, swap the values of the two qubits that are being swapped. So in
        general, <m>\ket{xy} \xrightarrow{\text{SWAP}(1,2)} \ket{yx}</m>.</p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
      <title><c>CNOT</c> Gate</title>
      <p>The <c>CNOT</c> gate is a little tricky. When applying the gate, we need to keep track of which
        qubit is the <term>control</term>, and which qubit is the <term>target</term>. The general
        convention to indicate which is which is with an arrow:</p>
      <md>\text{CNOT}(\text{control} \rightarrow \text{target})</md>
      <p>If for a given term the <em>
          control</em> is 1, then we flip the <em>target</em> qubit. Otherwise, the term does not
        change. For example, if we are applying a <c>CNOT</c> gate where the first qubit is the control
        and the second qubit is the target:</p>
      <md>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{11}
        \xrightarrow{\text{CNOT}(1 \rightarrow 2)}
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{00} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\ket{10}</md>

      <p>In the first term, the control is 0, so this term does not change. In the second term, the
        control is 1, so we flip the second qubit in the term.</p>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>
      <insert>exercises, 2 or 3</insert>
    </p>

    <p>While bra-ket notation is handy to keep track of probabilities and calculate simple gates,
      it starts becoming more and more unwieldy with more gates and more complex states. Is there
      perhaps another mathematical model we can use to help us out?</p>
  </section>
</section>
